cs.SY, cs.AI, cs.SE, cs.NI, cs.CE 

Reasoning: 
- cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a data-driven approach to detect switching actions and topology transitions in distribution networks, which involves real-time analysis of time-series voltage measurements. This falls under the domain of systems and control. 
- cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The proposed algorithm is based on comparison of actual voltage measurements with a library of signatures derived from possible topologies simulation. This involves the use of machine learning techniques and falls under the domain of artificial intelligence. 
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): The paper proposes an algorithm for detecting topology transitions in distribution networks, which involves software development and implementation. This falls under the domain of software engineering. 
- cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper deals with the analysis of time-series voltage measurements in distribution networks, which involves the use of networking and internet architecture concepts. 
- cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The proposed algorithm involves the simulation of possible topologies and the comparison of actual voltage measurements with a library of signatures. This falls under the domain of computational engineering.
